const e="allianz-doc-classification",t={title:"IDAS Prompt Management",subtitle:"Configuration and governance layer for Allianz's AI document classification system",company:"Allianz",year:"2025",duration:"6 months",role:"Product Designer",team_size:"20",cover_color:"#003781",tags:["Enterprise UX","AI Tooling","Design Systems","B2B"]},n=[{id:"overview",label:"Overview",type:"hero",data:{headline:"Making AI classification something you can vouch for.",body:"Allianz processes thousands of incoming documents every day — claims, invoices, legal notices, correspondence. IDAS is the internal system that uses AI to classify each one and route it to the right team. This tool is the layer that controls how that AI thinks. It lets business configurators write, test, and publish the prompts that drive classification — without ever involving engineering.",image:null,stats:[{label:"Year",value:"Nov 2025"},{label:"Duration",value:"6 months"},{label:"My Role",value:"Solo Designer"},{label:"Team",value:"20 people"}]}},{id:"problem",label:"The Problem",type:"statement",creative_direction:{tone:"precise",notes:"Heavy, deliberate reveal — this is the weight of the problem. Symmetric ease conveys constraint."},motion_spec:{enter:"fade_up",duration:.85,easing:"symmetric",y_enter:40},data:{eyebrow:"The Problem",headline:"The bottleneck wasn't speed. It was certainty.",body:`Before IDAS, document triage was manual. Skilled claims handlers spent hours every day doing mechanical routing — reading documents, categorizing them, forwarding to the right queue. Not analysis. Not decision-making. Just sorting.

When the AI was introduced, the problem didn't disappear — it shape-shifted. The AI was fast. But when it was wrong, no one knew until something downstream broke. And when it was right, handlers still double-checked everything, because there was no way to know which result to trust. The volume was there. The confidence wasn't.`}},{id:"before-after",label:"The Shift",type:"before_after",creative_direction:{tone:"contrast",notes:"Before items slide from left (old way), after items slide from right (new way). The left-right opposition is literal."},motion_spec:{enter:"fade_up",duration:.6,easing:"fast_out"},data:{eyebrow:"Before → After",before:{label:"Before this tool",items:["Prompt changes required an engineering ticket — 3+ day turnaround","No test environment — every change went straight to production","Confidence scores invisible: 55% looked the same as 95%","Misclassifications surfaced hours later, downstream, untraceable","Domain expertise lived in Slack threads and spreadsheets, never in the system"]},after:{label:"With IDAS prompt management",items:["Business configurators write and publish prompts independently, same day","Safe sandbox: test against real documents before anything goes live","Three-tier color signal (green/amber/red) makes confidence instantly readable","Errors visible before publishing — not after something breaks downstream","Domain knowledge encoded directly into the system by the people who have it"]}}},{id:"scope",label:"What This Tool Is",type:"insight_cards",creative_direction:{tone:"methodical",notes:"Items stagger in one-by-one — each scope point lands with weight. Measured timing reflects enterprise rigor."},motion_spec:{enter:"fade_up",duration:.7,stagger:.12,y_enter:24,easing:"fast_out"},data:{eyebrow:"Scope",items:[{icon:"🧠",headline:"Users = business configurators",body:"Not ops staff. Not ML engineers. People with deep domain knowledge who had never had a direct way to encode that knowledge into the system — until now. The interface had to work for someone who understood insurance documents fluently but had never written a line of code."},{icon:"⚙️",headline:"Engineering dependency eliminated",body:"Before this tool, changing prompt logic required raising an engineering ticket and waiting 3+ days for deployment. Business teams had workarounds — spreadsheets, shared docs, informal Slack threads — that tracked what the prompts were supposed to do but couldn't actually change them."},{icon:"🔄",headline:"Full lifecycle in one place",body:"Write, test against real documents, get approval, publish, monitor performance. The tool needed to cover every stage — not just authoring. Without a safe testing environment and a clear publish gate, configurators couldn't trust what they were changing or when it went live."}]}},{id:"insight",label:"Key Insight",type:"text_media",creative_direction:{tone:"reframe",notes:"Slides in from right — feels like a pivot moment. The insight reframes the whole project."},motion_spec:{enter:"slide_right",duration:.8,easing:"fast_out",y_enter:36},data:{layout:"text_left",eyebrow:"Key Insight",headline:"Users don't fear AI being wrong. They fear being wrong without knowing it.",body:`The early assumption was that the design problem was accuracy — help users write better prompts so the AI gets more classifications right. That shifted quickly once I got into conversations with the configurator team.

What came up wasn't frustration with incorrect outputs. It was frustration with invisible ones. When a classification came back wrong and a document went to the wrong queue, there was no alert, no signal. The error surfaced hours or days later, downstream — and by then it was hard to trace back.

That reframed everything. The goal wasn't to make the AI more accurate. It was to make the AI's uncertainty legible — so configurators could act on it, not just be surprised by it.`,image:!0,image_hint:"Diagram: two identical classification result rows side-by-side — one 55% confidence, one 95% — both displaying with no visual difference, to illustrate the invisibility problem"}},{id:"research-methods",label:"How I Learned",type:"research_method",data:{eyebrow:"How I learned what the tool needed",methods:[{icon:"💬",name:"Ongoing configurator conversations",description:"Informal conversations with 1–2 business configurators across the 6-month project — focused on current prompt-editing workflow, trust in AI output, and frustrations with the existing process.",sample:"n=1–2, ongoing",tag:"qual"},{icon:"👁",name:"Workflow observation",description:"Informal sessions watching configurators attempt to understand classification results in the existing tool. Not structured usability testing — observation of real work as it happened.",sample:"same configurators",tag:"qual"},{icon:"🔄",name:"Iterative prototype reviews",description:"Design reviews of early confidence-display variants (numeric vs. categorical) with configurators during design iteration. Reactions observed during reviews, not in controlled testing conditions.",sample:"same configurators, multiple rounds",tag:"qual"}]}},{id:"research-findings",label:"What I Heard",type:"insight_cards",creative_direction:{tone:"evidence",notes:"Three findings from configurator interviews — the cards make each insight discrete and scannable."},motion_spec:{enter:"fade_up",duration:.65,stagger:.1,easing:"fast_out"},data:{eyebrow:"What I heard",items:[{icon:"👁",headline:"Confidence was invisible",body:"A 55% result and a 95% result looked identical. Configurators had no way to know which classifications to trust and which to question."},{icon:"⏱",headline:"Errors surfaced too late",body:"Misclassifications only appeared downstream — hours or days later — after a document had already gone to the wrong queue and caused work for someone else."},{icon:"🔒",headline:"Knowledge was locked out",body:"Domain experts knew exactly what the prompts should say. But without a safe way to test, most avoided touching them entirely — fear of breaking production."}]}},{id:"decisions",label:"Design Decisions",type:"pinned_cards",creative_direction:{tone:"methodical",notes:"Slower stagger — each decision deserves to breathe. This is the core design rationale section."},motion_spec:{enter:"fade_up",duration:.75,stagger:.15,y_enter:28,easing:"symmetric"},data:{eyebrow:"Design Decisions",headline:"Three decisions that redefined what the product needed to be.",items:[{number:"01",title:"Confidence as color, not as a number",description:`**Problem →** The AI returns a confidence score on every classification. Early designs showed this as a percentage. When reviewing early numeric confidence variants with configurators, no one acted on the score — most treated it as a system-internal readout, not a signal they were meant to interpret.

**A:** Show confidence as a percentage — technically precise, preserves full information. **B:** Three-tier color system: green (80%+), amber (60–79%), red (below 60%).

**Chose B** — configurators can now scan a test result and instantly know which rows need attention. **Cost:** The three tiers collapse fine-grained differences. A 79% and a 62% result look identical. Configurators lose the ability to distinguish within the amber band.`},{number:"02",title:"A publish lifecycle, not instant deploy",description:`**Problem →** The first version had a single 'Save' button — saving a prompt meant it went live immediately. Two configurators kept personal logs of every change in case they needed to roll back manually. The fear of breaking production meant most people avoided touching prompts at all.

**A:** Save = publish — immediate deployment, simple mental model, no extra steps. **B:** Three-stage lifecycle: Draft → Tested → Approved & Published.

**Chose B** — teams that had been avoiding edits for weeks started iterating daily once they had a safe staging state. **Cost:** Three stages add cognitive overhead for simple changes. A configurator making a minor wording fix must still move through the full cycle.`},{number:"03",title:"Plain language over technical precision",description:`**Problem →** Early iterations used ML-accurate terminology throughout: 'inference threshold', 'classification schema', 'token boundary'. Every term was correct. None meant anything to a business configurator who'd never written a line of code.

**A:** Keep technical terminology — precise, consistent with engineering docs, no translation layer. **B:** Rewrite the UI layer in plain language; preserve technical terms in docs and API surfaces only. The ML team pushed back on B, arguing that renaming terms would break communication when configurators escalated issues to engineers.

**Chose B** — someone with zero ML background can use the tool fluently after a 20-minute onboarding. **Cost:** Power users who want to understand the ML layer must context-switch between two vocabularies — plain language in the UI, technical terms in the docs.`}]}},{id:"demo",label:"Try It",type:"demo",data:{eyebrow:"Interactive Demo",headline:"What the AI sees — and what you couldn't.",description:"Every document in this queue has already been classified. The confidence scores exist. Toggle the signal to see what was invisible before.",variant:"confidence_scanner"}},{id:"outcome",label:"What Changed",type:"statement",meta:{intent:"prove",density:"low",max_words:80,max_blocks:1,proof_required:"none",disclosure:"inline"},data:{eyebrow:"Outcome",text:"I didn't run formal measurement after launch. What I saw: configurators who had avoided touching prompts for weeks started iterating daily — not because anyone asked them to, but because a safe place to try now existed."}},{id:"takeaway",label:"Takeaway",type:"word_reveal",data:{eyebrow:"Lesson learned",text:"The instinct is always to hide uncertainty. But hiding it doesn't make it go away — it just moves the cost downstream. Design for the moment the AI is wrong, not just the moment it's right.",emojis:["📄","🤖","⚡","🧠","✅","🔍","⚠️"]}}],o={id:e,meta:t,sections:n};export{o as default,e as id,t as meta,n as sections};
